            Privacy isn't about hiding illegal activity‚Äîit's about controlling your own information. Would you let strangers read your emails, medical records, or diary because you have "nothing to hide"? Privacy is a fundamental right, not a privilege for criminals.
          </p>
          <p class="text-gray-700 text-sm leading-relaxed">
            Plus, "nothing to hide" assumes governments never abuse power. History proves otherwise: McCarthyism, COINTELPRO, mass surveillance of activists. What's legal today may not be tomorrow.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section id="public-wifi" class="mb-12">
        <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4">3. Public WiFi is a Security Nightmare</h2>

        <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">
          That free WiFi at Starbucks, airports, or hotels? It's a <strong>hacker's playground</strong>. Public networks are unencrypted, meaning anyone on the same network can intercept your traffic.
        </p>

        <div class="bg-red-50 border-2 border-red-500 rounded-lg p-6 my-6">
          <h3 class="font-bold text-red-900 mb-4">üö® Attacks on Public WiFi</h3>

          <div class="space-y-4">
            <div class="border-l-4 border-red-600 pl-4">
              <h4 class="font-bold text-gray-900">Man-in-the-Middle (MITM) Attacks</h4>
              <p class="text-sm text-gray-700 mt-1">
                Attacker intercepts traffic between you and websites. Can steal passwords, credit card numbers, session cookies, and inject malware into unencrypted HTTP pages.
              </p>
            </div>

            <div class="border-l-4 border-red-600 pl-4">
              <h4 class="font-bold text-gray-900">Evil Twin Attacks</h4>
              <p class="text-sm text-gray-700 mt-1">
                Hacker creates fake WiFi hotspot named "Starbucks WiFi" or "Airport_Free_WiFi". Users connect thinking it's legitimate, and attacker captures all traffic.
              </p>
            </div>

            <div class="border-l-4 border-red-600 pl-4">
              <h4 class="font-bold text-gray-900">Packet Sniffing</h4>
              <p class="text-sm text-gray-700 mt-1">
                Tools like Wireshark can capture all unencrypted traffic on public WiFi. Attackers can see passwords, emails, messages, and browsing history in real-time.
              </p>
            </div>

            <div class="border-l-4 border-red-600 pl-4">
              <h4 class="font-bold text-gray-900">Session Hijacking</h4>
              <p class="text-sm text-gray-700 mt-1">
                Even with HTTPS, some cookies are transmitted unencrypted. Attackers steal session cookies to impersonate you and access accounts without passwords.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-green-50 border-l-4 border-green-600 rounded-lg p-6 my-6">
          <h3 class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-3">‚úÖ How a VPN Protects You on Public WiFi</h3>
          <p class="text-gray-700 text-sm leading-relaxed">
            A VPN encrypts all traffic from your device to the VPN server, creating a secure tunnel even on compromised networks. Attackers only see encrypted gibberish‚Äîthey can't intercept passwords, steal cookies, or perform MITM attacks. This is the #1 reason security experts recommend VPNs.
          </p>
        </div>

        <p class="text-gray-700 text-sm italic mt-6">
          <strong>Rule of thumb:</strong> Never access banking, email, or sensitive accounts on public WiFi without a VPN. Period.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section id="geo-restrictions" class="mb-12">
